{"title_page": "SS Gracechurch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}} \n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}} \n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country= [[United Kingdom]]\n|Ship flag= {{shipboxflag|UK|civil}}\n|Ship name='''''Gracechurch'''''<ref name=ShipsListSutherland>{{cite web |url=http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/bjsutherland.htm |title=B.J. Sutherland & Co., Ltd. Newcastle upon Tyne 1892-1954 |last=Swiggum |first=S |date=1997\u20132010 |work=The Ships List |publisher=S Swiggum, M Kohli |accessdate=26 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610202006/http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/bjsutherland.htm |archivedate=10 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Ship owner=Gracechurch Shipping Co.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship operator=James, Muers & Co.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship ordered= \n|Ship builder=[[William Doxford & Sons]], Sunderland<ref name=LR32>{{cite book |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=33b0363.pdf |year=1932 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=25 February 1930<ref name=U499/>\n|Ship completed=April 1930<ref name=LR32/><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} [[London]]<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship identification=*[[Code Letters]] LFSR\n*{{ICS|Lima}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Sierra}}{{ICS|Romeo}}<ref name=LR32/>\n*UK [[official number]] 161390<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship out of service=1933<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship fate=Sold<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship name='''''Peebles'''''<ref name=LR35>{{cite book |url= http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=35b0968.pdf |year=1935 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>\n|Ship owner=[[Arthur Sutherland|B.J. Sutherland & Co]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship operator=B.J. Sutherland & Co\n|Ship acquired=1933<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship out of service=1936<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship fate=Sold\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship name='''''Mill Hill'''''<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship namesake=[[Mill Hill]], north London\n|Ship owner=Mill Hill Steam Ship Co, Ltd.<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship operator=[[Counties Ship Management]] Co Ltd, [[London]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/><ref name=U499>{{cite web|url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/499.html |title=Mill Hill |last=Helgason |first=Gu\u00f0mundur |date=1995\u20132010 |work=uboat.net |publisher=Gu\u00f0mundur Helgason |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=1936<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} Newcastle-upon-Tyne<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship identification=*[[Call sign#Ships and boats|call sign]] GTJL\n*{{ICS|Golf}}{{ICS|Tango}}{{ICS|Juliet}}{{ICS|Lima}}<ref name=LR35/>\n*UK official number 161390<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by torpedo 30 August 1940<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type=[[cargo ship]]\n|Ship tonnage=*{{GRT|4318}};<ref name=LR32/>\n*tonnage under deck 4,025;<ref name=LR32/>\n*{{NRT|2600}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|320.4|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship beam={{convert|52.9|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship height={{convert|24.9|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=368 [[Horsepower#Nominal horsepower|NHP]]<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship propulsion=3-cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engine]];<ref name=LR32/> single [[Propeller|screw]]\n|Ship speed= \n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship crew=34<ref name=U499/>\n|Ship armament= \n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Gracechurch''''' was a [[United Kingdom|UK]] {{GRT|4318}} [[cargo ship]] built by [[William Doxford & Sons]] at [[Pallion]] on [[River Wear|Wearside]] in 1930.<ref name=LR32/> She twice changed owners and names, becoming '''SS ''Peebles''''' in 1933 and '''SS ''Mill Hill''''' in 1936. She was sunk by a German submarine in August 1940.\n\n==Engines==\nThe ship had nine corrugated furnaces with a combined grate area of {{convert|187|sqft|0}} feeding three 180 [[Pounds per square inch|lb<sub>f</sub>/in<sup>2</sup>]] single-ended boilers with a combined heating surface of {{convert|6105|sqft|0}}.<ref name=LR32/>\n\n==Names and owners==\n''Gracechurch'' was first owned by Gracechurch Shipping Co of Newcastle and managed by James, Muers & Co of [[Cardiff]].<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1933 she was sold to [[Arthur Sutherland|B.J. Sutherland & Co]] who renamed her ''Peebles''.\n\nIn 1936 she was sold to the Mill Hill Steam Ship Co Ltd,<ref name=LR35/> which was controlled by [[Counties Ship Management]] (an offshoot of the Rethymnis & Kulukundis shipbroking company of London<ref name=CSM1>{{cite web |url= http://www.lof-news.co.uk/CountiesHistory/Counties1.htm |title=Counties Ship Management 1934-2007 |last=Fenton |first=Roy |year=2006 |work=LOF-News |publisher= |page=1 |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>) who renamed her ''Mill Hill''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n\n==Loss==\n{{location map|UK Scotland|relief=1|width=304\n|lat= 58.48\n|long= -6.49\n|caption=Approximate position of ''Gracechurch''{{'}}s wreck\n|AlternativeMap= \n}}\nOn 16 August 1940 ''Mill Hill'' left [[City of Halifax|Halifax, Nova Scotia]] as a member of [[HX convoys|convoy HX 66A]] laden with pig iron and scrap steel{{sfn|Slader|1988|p=63}} for [[Middlesbrough]], England.<ref name=U499/> Between 0220 and 0248 hrs on 30 August 58 miles off [[Cape Wrath]] in the north of Scotland ''{{GS|U-32|1937|2}}'' torpedoed the convoy, sinking three ships.<ref name=U499/> One was ''Mill Hill'', which sank within a few minutes with the loss of all hands.<ref name=U499/>\n\n==Replacement ships==\n''Gracechurch'' was the third of four ships that B.J. Sutherland & Co named ''Peebles''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> When Sutherland sold her in 1936, William Doxford & Sons completed a new 4,982 ton cargo ship MV ''Peebles'' for Sutherland.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> She survived the Second World War and in 1951 Sutherland sold her to [[Wesfarmers|Westralian Farmers Transport]] who renamed her ''Swanstream''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1957 Westralian sold to J. Manners & Co. of [[Hong Kong]] who renamed her ''San Fernando''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1965 Manners sold to her to Yong & Lee Timber who renamed her ''Phoenician Star''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> She was scrapped at Hong Kong in 1967.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n\n''Gracechurch'' was the first of two ships that Counties Ship Management named ''Mill Hill''. In 1947 CSM bought the 7,219 ton [[Liberty ship]] [[List of Liberty ships (S\u2013Z)|SS ''Samdon'']] and renamed her SS ''Mill Hill''. ''Samdon'' had been built by [[New England Shipbuilding Corporation]] of [[Portland, Maine]] in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/ship.php?ship_id=34019&name=Samdon |year=1943 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref> In 1949 she was transferred from CSM to a new Rethymnis and Kulukundis company, [[London and Overseas Freighters]], retaining the name ''Mill Hill''. In 1951 LOF sold her to new owners who renamed her ''Educator''.<ref name=CSM1/> She was scrapped in [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania in 1961.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsS.html |title=Liberty Ships - S |date= |work=Mariners |publisher= |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources & further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Sedgwick |first=Stanley |editor1-last=Kinnaird |editor1-first=Mark |editor2-last=O'Donoghue |editor2-first=K.J. |title=London & Overseas Freighters, 1948-92: A Short History |origyear=1992 |year=1993 |publisher=[[World Ship Society]] |location= |isbn=0-905617-68-1 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sedgwick |first1=Stanley |last2=Sprake |first2=R.F. |title=London & Overseas Freighters Limited 1949-1977 |year=1977 |publisher=[[World Ship Society]] |location= |isbn= 0905617037 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Slader |first=John |title=The Red Duster at War |year=1988 |publisher=William Kimber & Co Ltd |location=London |isbn=0-7183-0679-1 |page=63 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{coord|58.48|N|06.49|W|display=title}}\n{{August 1940 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gracechurch}}\n[[Category:1930 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1940]]\n[[Category:Ships lost with all hands]]\n[[Category:Ships of Counties Ship Management]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by German submarines in World War II]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Wear]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War II shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}} \n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=\n|Ship caption=\n}} \n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country= [[United Kingdom]]\n|Ship flag= {{shipboxflag|UK|civil}}\n|Ship name='''''Gracechurch'''''<ref name=ShipsListSutherland>{{cite web |url=http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/bjsutherland.htm |title=B.J. Sutherland & Co., Ltd. Newcastle upon Tyne 1892-1954 |last=Swiggum |first=S |date=1997\u20132010 |work=The Ships List |publisher=S Swiggum, M Kohli |accessdate=26 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610202006/http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/bjsutherland.htm |archivedate=10 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|Ship owner=Gracechurch Shipping Co.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship operator=James, Muers & Co.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship ordered= \n|Ship builder=[[William Doxford & Sons]], Sunderland<ref name=LR32>{{cite book |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=33b0363.pdf |year=1932 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=25 February 1930<ref name=U499/>\n|Ship completed=April 1930<ref name=LR32/><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} [[London]]<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship identification=*[[Code Letters]] LFSR\n*{{ICS|Lima}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Sierra}}{{ICS|Romeo}}<ref name=LR32/>\n*UK [[official number]] 161390<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship out of service=1933<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship fate=Sold<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship name='''''Peebles'''''<ref name=LR35>{{cite book |url= http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=35b0968.pdf |year=1935 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>\n|Ship owner=[[Arthur Sutherland|B.J. Sutherland & Co]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship operator=B.J. Sutherland & Co\n|Ship acquired=1933<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship out of service=1936<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship fate=Sold\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship name='''''Mill Hill'''''<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship namesake=[[Mill Hill]], north London\n|Ship owner=Mill Hill Steam Ship Co, Ltd.<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship operator=[[Counties Ship Management]] Co Ltd, [[London]]<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/><ref name=U499>{{cite web|url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/499.html |title=Mill Hill |last=Helgason |first=Gu\u00f0mundur |date=1995\u20132010 |work=uboat.net |publisher=Gu\u00f0mundur Helgason |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>\n|Ship acquired=1936<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|UK|civil}} Newcastle-upon-Tyne<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship identification=*[[Call sign#Ships and boats|call sign]] GTJL\n*{{ICS|Golf}}{{ICS|Tango}}{{ICS|Juliet}}{{ICS|Lima}}<ref name=LR35/>\n*UK official number 161390<ref name=LR35/>\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by torpedo 30 August 1940<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/><ref name=U499/>\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type=[[cargo ship]]\n|Ship tonnage=*{{GRT|4318}};<ref name=LR32/>\n*tonnage under deck 4,025;<ref name=LR32/>\n*{{NRT|2600}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|320.4|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship beam={{convert|52.9|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship height={{convert|24.9|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=368 [[Horsepower#Nominal horsepower|NHP]]<ref name=LR32/>\n|Ship propulsion=3-cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engine]];<ref name=LR32/> single [[Propeller|screw]]\n|Ship speed= \n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship crew=34<ref name=U499/>\n|Ship armament= \n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Gracechurch''''' was a [[United Kingdom|UK]] {{GRT|4318}} [[cargo ship]] built by [[William Doxford & Sons]] at [[Pallion]] on [[River Wear|Wearside]] in 1930.<ref name=LR32/> She twice changed owners and names, becoming '''SS ''Peebles''''' in 1933 and '''SS ''Mill Hill''''' in 1936. She was sunk by a German submarine in August 1940.\n\n==Engines==\nThe ship had nine corrugated furnaces with a combined grate area of {{convert|187|sqft|0}} feeding three 180 [[Pounds per square inch|lb<sub>f</sub>/in<sup>2</sup>]] single-ended boilers with a combined heating surface of {{convert|6105|sqft|0}}.<ref name=LR32/>\n\n==Names and owners==\n''Gracechurch'' was first owned by Gracechurch Shipping Co of Newcastle and managed by James, Muers & Co of [[Cardiff]].<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1933 she was sold to [[Arthur Sutherland|B.J. Sutherland & Co]] who renamed her ''Peebles''.\n\nIn 1936 she was sold to the Mill Hill Steam Ship Co Ltd,<ref name=LR35/> which was controlled by [[Counties Ship Management]] (an offshoot of the Rethymnis & Kulukundis shipbroking company of London<ref name=CSM1>{{cite web |url= http://www.lof-news.co.uk/CountiesHistory/Counties1.htm |title=Counties Ship Management 1934-2007 |last=Fenton |first=Roy |year=2006 |work=LOF-News |publisher= |page=1 |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>) who renamed her ''Mill Hill''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n\n==Loss==\n{{location map|UK Scotland|relief=1|width=304\n|lat= 58.48\n|long= -6.49\n|caption=Approximate position of ''Gracechurch''{{'}}s wreck\n|AlternativeMap= \n}}\nOn 16 August 1940 ''Mill Hill'' left [[City of Halifax|Halifax, Nova Scotia]] as a member of [[HX convoys|convoy HX 66A]] laden with pig iron and scrap steel{{sfn|Slader,|1988|p=63}} for [[Middlesbrough]], England.<ref name=U499/> Between 0220 and 0248 hrs on 30 August 58 miles off [[Cape Wrath]] in the north of Scotland ''{{GS|U-32|1937|2}}'' torpedoed the convoy, sinking three ships.<ref name=U499/> One was ''Mill Hill'', which sank within a few minutes with the loss of all hands.<ref name=U499/>\n\n==Replacement ships==\n''Gracechurch'' was the third of four ships that B.J. Sutherland & Co named ''Peebles''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> When Sutherland sold her in 1936, William Doxford & Sons completed a new 4,982 ton cargo ship MV ''Peebles'' for Sutherland.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> She survived the Second World War and in 1951 Sutherland sold her to [[Wesfarmers|Westralian Farmers Transport]] who renamed her ''Swanstream''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1957 Westralian sold to J. Manners & Co. of [[Hong Kong]] who renamed her ''San Fernando''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> In 1965 Manners sold to her to Yong & Lee Timber who renamed her ''Phoenician Star''.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/> She was scrapped at Hong Kong in 1967.<ref name=ShipsListSutherland/>\n\n''Gracechurch'' was the first of two ships that Counties Ship Management named ''Mill Hill''. In 1947 CSM bought the 7,219 ton [[Liberty ship]] [[List of Liberty ships (S\u2013Z)|SS ''Samdon'']] and renamed her SS ''Mill Hill''. ''Samdon'' had been built by [[New England Shipbuilding Corporation]] of [[Portland, Maine]] in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/ship.php?ship_id=34019&name=Samdon |year=1943 |title=Lloyd's Register of Shipping |location=London |publisher=[[Lloyd's Register]] |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref> In 1949 she was transferred from CSM to a new Rethymnis and Kulukundis company, [[London and Overseas Freighters]], retaining the name ''Mill Hill''. In 1951 LOF sold her to new owners who renamed her ''Educator''.<ref name=CSM1/> She was scrapped in [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania in 1961.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsS.html |title=Liberty Ships - S |date= |work=Mariners |publisher= |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources & further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Sedgwick |first=Stanley |editor1-last=Kinnaird |editor1-first=Mark |editor2-last=O'Donoghue |editor2-first=K.J. |title=London & Overseas Freighters, 1948-92: A Short History |origyear=1992 |year=1993 |publisher=[[World Ship Society]] |location= |isbn=0-905617-68-1 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sedgwick |first1=Stanley |last2=Sprake |first2=R.F. |title=London & Overseas Freighters Limited 1949-1977 |year=1977 |publisher=[[World Ship Society]] |location= |isbn= 0905617037 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Slader |first=John |title=The Red Duster at War |year=1988 |publisher=William Kimber & Co Ltd |location=London |isbn=0-7183-0679-1 |page=63 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{coord|58.48|N|06.49|W|display=title}}\n{{August 1940 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gracechurch}}\n[[Category:1930 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1940]]\n[[Category:Ships lost with all hands]]\n[[Category:Ships of Counties Ship Management]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by German submarines in World War II]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Wear]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War II shipwrecks in the Atlantic Ocean]]\n", "name_user": "Headbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLoss:clean up, replaced: {{sfn|Slader, \u2192 {{sfn|Slader", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Gracechurch"}
